Australia
---
[1] National
Date: Sun 23 Jun 2019 12:00 AM
Source: The Age [edited]
https://www.theage.com.au/healthcare/early-surge-in-flu-cases-but-experts-hope-for-early-end-to-season-20190622-p520a2.html


There have been more than 1.5 times as many confirmed flu cases so far this year [2019] than in the whole of 2018, new data shows.

But despite the surge in early cases, experts say this year's season is not worse than average, and an early start to flu season could mean an early end.

This year [2019] to date there have been 97 920 laboratory-confirmed cases of influenza across Australia, compared with 58 870 cases for the whole of 2018, according to the latest data from the National Notifiable Diseases Surveillance System (NNDSS).

In the fortnight to [16 Jun 2019], there were 19 353 new cases of influenza alone -- "substantially higher" compared to the same period in the previous 5 years, according to the latest influenza surveillance report.

Experts say there are a number of reasons there have been so many influenza cases across Australia already this year.

Professor Robert Booy, an infectious diseases expert at the University of Sydney, said having 3 strains in circulation -- influenza A(H1N1), influenza A(H3N2), and influenza B -- "certainly makes things worse."

Another explanation, Professor Booy said, was that immunity is lower due to the quiet flu season in 2018. "We went from a very busy to a very quiet year, and as a consequence, as the virus mutates and changes the level of immunity in the community starts to fall off again, and therefore we may have a lot more susceptible people," he said.

There were also record numbers of summer flu cases, according to NSW [New South Wales] health director of communicable disease, Vicky Sheppeard. On top of that, she said the winter flu season started much earlier than normal.

"It started in the 2nd week of May 2019, so we're seeing the number of cases in June that we'd normally be seeing in August," Dr Sheppeard said.

The number of people being admitted to hospital with influenza is also high for this time of year.

Between [1 Apr and 16 Jun 2019], 840 people were admitted to hospital with confirmed influenza, and 146 of those people were admitted in the 2 weeks to [16 Jun 2019] -- more than 3 times the 5 year average for the same fortnight. There have also been 192 influenza-associated deaths so far this year, as reported to the NNDSS.

However, the total number of deaths, hospitalisations, and cases of influenza is also higher than these numbers suggest as not all influenza cases are reported, but Professor Booy said data collections and estimates have been improving every year.

"Every year we do more testing -- GPs do more testing, hospitals do more testing every year -- so we're getting closer to a more accurate estimate," he said.

Dr Sheppard said the number of hospitalisations and deaths from influenza were certainly high for the time of year, but were about average when compared to the number of influenza cases.

"In 2017 we saw an unusually high number of hospitalisations and deaths, whereas so far 2019 is more tracking along the average flu season, but just earlier than we'd normally see it," she said.

While it was hard to predict due to a different mix of viruses, Dr Sheppeard said this year's flu season could potentially end earlier.

"Normally flu seasons peak about 6 weeks after they start, and last about 12 weeks, 14 weeks," she said. "We can really only monitor it, but we're hoping that it will peak in the next couple of weeks and then the numbers will start to decline."

Professor Booy said influenza strains were constantly being analysed through the World Health Organisation flu collaborating centre in Melbourne, to check how the viruses were mutating and how well they were covered by the current vaccine.

While a flu vaccine won't prevent people from getting influenza 100 per cent of the time, Professor Booy said it does make a difference. "Essentially you can halve the risk of catching flu by vaccination," he said." It's not perfect, but it's more than helpful."

[Byline: Rachel Klun]

