[3] India (Maharashtra)
Date: Mon 1 Jul 2019 3:24 IST
Source: The Times of India, Times News Network (TNN) [edited]
https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/4-more-die-of-swine-flu-experts-warn-of-spike/articleshow/70016049.cms


According to the latest report by the state health department, 4 more people succumbed to swine flu [influenza A(H1N1)] in the state [Maharashtra] in the past 3 weeks, taking the toll to 189 till [27 Jun 2019].

Of these, Pune has recorded the highest -- 44 deaths -- followed by Nagpur (34), Nashik (31), Mumbai (18), and Kolhapur (12).

The transmission of the virus, experts say, is likely to rise during the monsoon as the drop in temperature provides a conducive atmosphere. "We have intensified our surveillance, so there is no need to panic," a state health official said.

"People should maintain healthy habits, exercise regularly, and sleep properly. Frequent hand-washing is a must during this period, as monsoon provides a conducive set-up for all kinds of influenza viruses, including [influenza A(H1N1)]," Mandeep Chadha, senior scientist at National Institute of Virology, said.

Officials said 1705 people had tested positive for the contagion in the state since the beginning of the year [2019]. "The season can spur transmission of viruses, including the [influenza A(H1N1)] virus. People should exercise caution," senior family physician Prakash Mahajan said.

Moreover, weakening immunity among the masses and the co-circulation of other seasonal viruses, along with [influenza A(H1N1)], are among the contributing factors. "People should be on the alert for persistent or worsening flu symptoms, particularly if one has other risk factors such as obesity or a compromised immune system," critical care expert Prasad Rajhans said.

"Delay in seeking treatment has been the cause for quite a few [influenza A(H1N1)] deaths reported in Pune since January this year [2019]. Often, patients go to doctors only after developing breathlessness and after their condition has worsened. Precious time is wasted in the 1st few days of showing symptoms, when treatment is crucial," Ramchandra Hankare, medical officer of health, Pune Municipal Corporation said.

[Byline: Umesh Isalkar]

